<TITLE> Update women's policy: Mohila Parishad </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 3 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh Mohila Parishad called on the law ministry Tuesday to enforce a 2001 High Court rule to end fatwas. "The 1997 women's policy should be reinstated to end gender discrimination and the policy must be modernised," said Mohila Parishad president Ayesha Khanam after a meeting with law minister Shafiq Ahmed. The meeting saw the delegation of women's leaders demand new laws be formulated in accordance with the High Court verdict of 2001 to put an end to fatwas, "The 5th and 8th amendment of the constitution should also be cancelled and new laws should be introduced in view of new policy against sexual harassment of women at institutes of higher education," Ayesha Khanam told reporters afterwards. "The Mohila Parishad wants reforms in prejudicial family law and equal rights of women in matters of divorce, parenthood, inheritance and other issues," she said. She said the law minister had assured all-out cooperation. bdnew
